**Sec. 30001**  
The Bureau of Consumer Financial Protection (BCFP) funding cap is reduced from $12 billion to $6.5 billion under the Consumer Financial Protection Act of 2010, as amended. This change limits the BCFP’s budget to $6.5 billion for fiscal year 2025, replacing the previous $12 billion cap. The amendment directly modifies Section 1017(a)(2)(A)(iii) of the Act, which governs the BCFP’s authority to fund consumer protection initiatives. The reduction aims to reallocate funds to other priorities under the bill.  

**Sec. 30002**  
The Green and Resilient Retrofit Program for Multifamily Housing, authorized by Public Law 117-169 (2022), is rescinded. Unobligated balances of funds allocated to this program are canceled, effectively ending its operations. The rescission applies to all amounts made available under Section 30002(a) of the bill, which was passed in 2022. This action removes financial support for retrofitting multifamily housing to meet climate resilience standards.  

**Sec. 30003**  
The Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) Reserve Fund is restructured to prioritize whistleblower awards. Subsection (i) of Section 4 of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 is deleted, and subsections (j) and (k) are renumbered as (i) and (j). The Fund is now available for unlimited use to pay whistleblower awards without requiring further appropriations. A transition period allows the SEC to use pre-existing funds until October 1, 2025, after which all balances are transferred to the general fund of the Treasury.  

**Sec. 30004**  
$1 billion is appropriated for fiscal year 2025 to support the Defense Production Act (DPA), remaining available until September 30, 2027. This funding is added to the DPA’s existing authority, which governs the Department of Defense’s ability to prioritize production of critical goods. The allocation is intended to bolster domestic manufacturing capabilities for national security and defense needs, including defense-related infrastructure projects. [end of text]


